        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Frequency setup
The molecular lines we plan to observe are CO (3-2) and 13CO (3-2), the most intense lines in typcial protoplanetary disks. Previous results have shown the CO lines can well trace the gas kinematics in GM Aur (Dutrey et al. 1998).

Required resolutions
The feature of the disk eccentricity is most clear just outside of the submillimeter cavity, and gradually declines to larger radii. The submillimeter cavity in GM Aur is ~28 AU (0.2"). Therefore, an angular resolution of 0.2" is required to resolve the gas motions around the cavity. The expected velocity deviation of eccentric disk motion from circular Keplerian rotation is ~0.2 km/s at the radius of the cavity and decreases to 0.05 km/s at the twice of the cavity radius. Therefore, a velocity resolution of 0.05 km/s (61 kHz) is reqiured to measure such velocity deviation. 

Sensitivity 
To perform our analysis and to detect the disk eccentricity at a level &gt; 2sigma, S/N &gt; 5 is required for the emission originated from the region surrounding the cavity. We have constructed a disk model of GM Aur based on observed density and temperature profiles (Dutrey et al. 1998), and estimated the CO (3-2) line intensity of such region is ~40 mJy per beam. Hence, we request a rms noise level of 8 mJy per beam to achieve S/N of 5. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
